<h1>Custom Elements</h1>
<p>
  <code>grigson</code> provides a set of custom elements for embedding live chord charts in HTML.
  <code>&lt;grigson-chart&gt;</code> handles parsing and transposition;
  renderer elements handle display. This page demonstrates the main usage patterns.
</p>

<h2>Inline template</h2>
<p>
  The simplest usage: place the chart source in a <code>&lt;template&gt;</code> child.
  The <code>normalise</code> attribute corrects enharmonic spelling for the detected key.
</p>
<pre><code>&lt;grigson-chart normalise&gt;
  &lt;template&gt;
---
title: Autumn Leaves
key: Gm
---
[A]
| Am7b5 | D7 | Gm | Gm |
| Am7b5 | D7 | Gm | Gm |
[B]
| Cm7 | F7 | Bbmaj7 | Bbmaj7 |
| Am7b5 | D7 | Gm | Gm |
  &lt;/template&gt;
&lt;/grigson-chart&gt;</code></pre>

<grigson-chart normalise>
  <template>
---
title: Autumn Leaves
key: Gm
---
[A]
| Am7b5 | D7 | Gm | Gm |
| Am7b5 | D7 | Gm | Gm |
[B]
| Cm7 | F7 | Bbmaj7 | Bbmaj7 |
| Am7b5 | D7 | Gm | Gm |
  </template>
</grigson-chart>

<h2>External template — multi-key transposition</h2>
<p>
  A single <code>&lt;template id="..."&gt;</code> can be referenced by multiple
  <code>&lt;grigson-chart&gt;</code> elements. Instruments that read in a different key need
  the chart transposed so the written pitches produce the correct concert pitches:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Concert pitch</strong> — no transposition</li>
  <li><strong>Bb instruments</strong> (trumpet, clarinet, tenor sax) — sound a major 2nd lower than written, so transpose up 2 semitones</li>
  <li><strong>Eb instruments</strong> (alto sax, baritone sax) — sound a major 6th lower than written, so transpose up 9 semitones</li>
</ul>
<pre><code>&lt;template id="autumn-leaves"&gt;
---
title: Autumn Leaves
key: Gm
---
[A]
| Am7b5 | D7 | Gm | Gm |
| Am7b5 | D7 | Gm | Gm |
[B]
| Cm7 | F7 | Bbmaj7 | Bbmaj7 |
| Am7b5 | D7 | Gm | Gm |
&lt;/template&gt;

&lt;!-- Concert pitch --&gt;
&lt;grigson-chart template="autumn-leaves" normalise&gt;&lt;/grigson-chart&gt;

&lt;!-- Bb instruments: transpose +2 semitones --&gt;
&lt;grigson-chart template="autumn-leaves" normalise transpose-semitones="2"&gt;&lt;/grigson-chart&gt;

&lt;!-- Eb instruments: transpose +9 semitones --&gt;
&lt;grigson-chart template="autumn-leaves" normalise transpose-semitones="9"&gt;&lt;/grigson-chart&gt;</code></pre>

<template id="autumn-leaves">
---
title: Autumn Leaves
key: Gm
---
[A]
| Am7b5 | D7 | Gm | Gm |
| Am7b5 | D7 | Gm | Gm |
[B]
| Cm7 | F7 | Bbmaj7 | Bbmaj7 |
| Am7b5 | D7 | Gm | Gm |
</template>

<h3>Concert pitch</h3>
<grigson-chart template="autumn-leaves" normalise></grigson-chart>

<h3>Bb instruments (+2 semitones)</h3>
<grigson-chart template="autumn-leaves" normalise transpose-semitones="2"></grigson-chart>

<h3>Eb instruments (+9 semitones)</h3>
<grigson-chart template="autumn-leaves" normalise transpose-semitones="9"></grigson-chart>

<h2>Explicit renderer — <code>&lt;grigson-html-renderer&gt;</code></h2>
<p>
  By default <code>&lt;grigson-chart&gt;</code> uses the built-in HTML renderer.
  You can make it explicit by adding a <code>&lt;grigson-html-renderer&gt;</code> child.
  This lets you target the renderer's CSS custom properties and shadow parts directly.
</p>
<pre><code>&lt;grigson-chart normalise&gt;
  &lt;grigson-html-renderer style="
    --grigson-chord-root-color: steelblue;
    --grigson-chord-suffix-color: tomato;
  "&gt;&lt;/grigson-html-renderer&gt;
  &lt;template&gt;
---
title: All The Things You Are
key: Ab
---
[A]
| Fm7 | Bbm7 | Eb7 | Abmaj7 |
| Dbmaj7 | G7 | Cmaj7 | Cmaj7 |
  &lt;/template&gt;
&lt;/grigson-chart&gt;</code></pre>

<grigson-chart normalise>
  <grigson-html-renderer style="
    --grigson-chord-root-color: steelblue;
    --grigson-chord-suffix-color: tomato;
  "></grigson-html-renderer>
  <template>
---
title: All The Things You Are
key: Ab
---
[A]
| Fm7 | Bbm7 | Eb7 | Abmaj7 |
| Dbmaj7 | G7 | Cmaj7 | Cmaj7 |
  </template>
</grigson-chart>

<h2>Third-party renderer — <code>&lt;grigson-text-renderer&gt;</code></h2>
<p>
  Any element implementing the <code>GrigsonRendererElement</code> interface can be used as
  the renderer. <code>&lt;grigson-text-renderer&gt;</code> is a separate package that renders
  charts as plain text inside a <code>&lt;pre&gt;</code> element, demonstrating the
  extensibility contract.
</p>
<pre><code>&lt;!-- Load the separate package --&gt;
&lt;script src="/js/grigson-text-renderer-register.iife.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;grigson-chart normalise&gt;
  &lt;grigson-text-renderer&gt;&lt;/grigson-text-renderer&gt;
  &lt;template&gt;
---
title: Autumn Leaves
key: Gm
---
[A]
| Am7b5 | D7 | Gm | Gm |
| Am7b5 | D7 | Gm | Gm |
[B]
| Cm7 | F7 | Bbmaj7 | Bbmaj7 |
| Am7b5 | D7 | Gm | Gm |
  &lt;/template&gt;
&lt;/grigson-chart&gt;</code></pre>

<grigson-chart normalise>
  <grigson-text-renderer></grigson-text-renderer>
  <template>
---
title: Autumn Leaves
key: Gm
---
[A]
| Am7b5 | D7 | Gm | Gm |
| Am7b5 | D7 | Gm | Gm |
[B]
| Cm7 | F7 | Bbmaj7 | Bbmaj7 |
| Am7b5 | D7 | Gm | Gm |
  </template>
</grigson-chart>
